DAY 001 ■ PHASE 1
Linux Internals — The Engine Under Everything

cgroups · Namespaces · systemd · /proc · /sys
TODAY'S GOAL: Understand exactly what a 'container' really is at the kernel level — before you ever run Docker.
TOOLS: [Linux] [systemd] [cgroups] [namespaces] [/proc]

WHY THIS MATTERS BEFORE ANYTHING ELSE
When an interviewer asks 'how does Docker work?' — the wrong answer is 'it packages your app.' The right answer
explains namespaces and cgroups. Every container, every Kubernetes pod, every cloud function is built on two Linux
kernel primitives: namespaces (isolation) and cgroups (resource limits). Once you understand these, Docker is obvious,
Kubernetes is logical, and you can debug things others cannot.

PART 1: NAMESPACES — HOW ISOLATION WORKS
A namespace makes a process think it is the only process on the system — or that it has its own network, its own
filesystem, its own process tree. The host kernel is shared; only the view is isolated. Linux has 8 namespace types:

NAMESPACE WHAT IT ISOLATES REAL EXAMPLE
PID Process IDs — container PID 1 ≠ host PID 1 Your container's nginx is PID 1. Host sees it as PID 4821.
NET Network interfaces, routing tables, iptables Each container gets its own eth0, own IP address.
MNT Mount points, filesystem view Container can't see /home/user on the host.
UTS Hostname, domain name Container has hostname 'myapp', host has 'prod-server-01'.
IPC POSIX message queues, shared memory Pevents inter-container shared memory attacks.
USER User/group IDs UID 0 (root) inside container = non-root UID on host.
CGROUP cgroup filesystem view Container can't see host cgroup hierarchy.
TIME System clock offsets (kernel 5.6+) Container can have different clock offset.

See namespaces live on your machine right now:

# List all namespaces on your host
lsns
# Output looks like:
# NS TYPE NPROCS PID USER COMMAND
# 4026531835 cgroup 185 1 root /sbin/init
# 4026531836 pid 185 1 root /sbin/init
# 4026531837 user 185 1 root /sbin/init
# Each number is a unique inode — the namespace's identity
# Now run a container and compare:
docker run -d --name test nginx
docker inspect test --format '{{.State.Pid}}' # get container PID
# Let's call it 4821
ls -la /proc/4821/ns/ # see its namespaces
# Output — notice DIFFERENT inode numbers = isolated namespaces:
# lrwxrwxrwx net -> net:[4026532504] ← different from host!
# lrwxrwxrwx pid -> pid:[4026532502] ← different from host!


■ KEY INSIGHT
A container IS just a regular Linux process. It has a PID on the host. The only difference is that kernel namespaces
give it a different VIEW of the system. Run 'ps aux' on your host and you will see every container's processes listed
there. This is why containers start in milliseconds — no VM, no boot sequence, just a process with restricted
visibility.
Build a mini-container with ZERO Docker — just kernel tools:
# unshare creates a process in new namespaces
# -p = new PID namespace -f = fork --mount-proc = fresh /proc
sudo unshare -p -f --mount-proc /bin/bash
# NOW INSIDE the 'container':
echo $$ # prints 1 — we are PID 1!
ps aux # only sees THIS shell — perfect isolation
hostname # still the host's hostname (no -u flag)
# Exit and try with UTS namespace too:
sudo unshare -p -f -u --mount-proc /bin/bash
hostname container-demo # set our own hostname
hostname # shows: container-demo
# Open another terminal on host: hostname → still shows original!


PART 2: CGROUPS — HOW RESOURCE LIMITS WORK
Namespaces give isolation. cgroups (control groups) give resource limits. Without cgroups, one container could consume
100% of CPU and starve all others — the 'noisy neighbour' problem. cgroups solve this. Kubernetes resource requests
and limits are implemented entirely using cgroups under the hood.
See what Docker sets up for you automatically:
# Run a container with CPU and memory limits
docker run -d --name limited --cpus='0.5' --memory='128m' nginx
# Find the container's PID
PID=$(docker inspect limited --format '{{.State.Pid}}')
echo $PID
# Look at the actual cgroup files Docker created:
cat /sys/fs/cgroup/cpu/docker/$(docker inspect limited --format
'{{.Id}}')/cpu.cfs_quota_us
# Output: 50000 ← 50,000 microseconds out of 100,000 = 50% = 0.5 CPU
cat /sys/fs/cgroup/memory/docker/$(docker inspect limited --format
'{{.Id}}')/memory.limit_in_bytes
# Output: 134217728 ← 128 * 1024 * 1024 = 128MB


■ CONNECT THE DOTS — Kubernetes Resource Limits
When you write 'resources: limits: cpu: 500m memory: 128Mi' in a Kubernetes manifest, kubelet translates that
directly into the same cgroup files you see above. cpu: 500m = 0.5 CPU = 50,000 microseconds quota. This is why
you need to understand Linux before you can truly debug Kubernetes resource issues


PART 3: systemd — The Init System
systemd is PID 1 on every modern Linux system. It manages services, dependencies, and — crucially — it uses cgroups
internally to manage service resource limits. Understanding systemd is essential for debugging services in VMs, cloud
instances, and bare metal.
# Key systemd commands you need to know cold:
systemctl list-units --type=service --state=running # all running services
systemctl status nginx # detailed status + last logs
systemctl start|stop|restart|reload nginx # lifecycle
systemctl enable nginx # start on boot (creates symlink in /etc/systemd/system)
systemctl disable nginx # remove symlink
# Investigate a failed service:
systemctl --failed # list all failed units
journalctl -u nginx -n 50 --no-pager # last 50 log lines for nginx
journalctl -u nginx --since '1 hour ago' # time-filtered logs
journalctl -p err -b # all errors since last boot
# systemd unit file — this is how services are defined:
cat /etc/systemd/system/multi-user.target.wants/nginx.service


PART 4: /proc and /sys — The Kernel's Interface
/proc is not a real filesystem — it is a virtual interface to the kernel. Every file you read from /proc is generated live by the
kernel. Senior engineers know this is where you go to get the truth about what is happening.
# /proc// contains everything about a process:
cat /proc/1/cmdline | tr '\0' ' ' # full command line of PID 1 (init/systemd)
cat /proc/self/status # YOUR process's info
cat /proc/self/maps # memory map of current shell
cat /proc/meminfo # system memory breakdown
cat /proc/cpuinfo # CPU details
cat /proc/net/tcp # all TCP connections (raw hex)
# /sys/fs/cgroup = cgroup hierarchy (resource management)
ls /sys/fs/cgroup/ # show all cgroup controllers
cat /sys/fs/cgroup/memory/memory.stat # system-wide memory stats
# Read network statistics for debugging:
cat /proc/net/sockstat # socket summary
cat /proc/sys/net/core/somaxconn # max socket listen queue
# Change it live (no restart needed!):
echo 65535 | sudo tee /proc/sys/net/core/somaxconn
# Make it permanent:
echo 'net.core.somaxconn=65535' | sudo tee -a /etc/sysctl.conf
sudo sysctl -p


■ HANDS-ON LAB — Build Isolation From Scratch
Estimated time: 45 minutes. Do every step. Don't skip.
■ 1. Run 'lsns' and record the PID namespace inode number for PID 1
■ 2. Run 'docker run -d --name lab1 nginx' then inspect /proc/$(docker inspect lab1 --format '{{.State.Pid}}')/ns/ — write
down 3 namespaces that differ from PID 1.
■ 3. Run 'sudo unshare -p -f --mount-proc bash' — confirm you are PID 1 inside with 'echo $$'. Run 'ps aux' — how many
processes do you see? Exit.
■ 4. Run 'sudo unshare -p -f -u --mount-proc bash'. Set hostname to your name. Open a second terminal and confirm the
host hostname is unchanged.
■ 5. Run 'docker run -d --name mem-test --memory=50m stress stress --vm 1 --vm-bytes 100M'. Watch it get OOMKilled:
'docker stats mem-test' for 10 seconds.
■ 6. Read the OOM kill from the kernel: 'dmesg | grep -i oom | tail -5'. This is what you will do in production when pods die
mysteriously.
■ 7. Run 'systemctl list-units --type=service --failed'. If any are failed, read the logs with journalctl -u -n 20.
■ 8. Read /proc/self/status. Find your process's VmRSS (resident memory). Find your UID and GID.
